Cool.

00:02:59.280 --> 00:03:03.480
So today we're going to
start talking a little bit

00:03:03.480 --> 00:03:07.220
about photography and
why it is something

00:03:07.220 --> 00:03:08.972
that is really important to me.

00:03:08.972 --> 00:03:10.680
And the reason I want
to kind of bring up

00:03:10.680 --> 00:03:14.330
that initial subject is
because I think that people,

00:03:14.330 --> 00:03:15.830
along the way as
you do photography,

00:03:15.830 --> 00:03:19.340
the more you do it, you kind
of forget why you picked it up

00:03:19.340 --> 00:03:20.934
in the first place.

00:03:20.934 --> 00:03:23.100
People get a little bit
distracted with the business

00:03:23.100 --> 00:03:26.860
side of things, about earning
money, they start shooting,

00:03:26.860 --> 00:03:28.480
and then they get
bored along the way.

00:03:28.480 --> 00:03:30.510
And for me, photography
is a whole bunch

00:03:30.510 --> 00:03:34.850
of things that incidentally
are related, too,

00:03:34.850 --> 00:03:39.540
but aren't entirely
what makes what it is.

00:03:39.540 --> 00:03:41.200
So that sentence
doesn't make sense.

00:03:41.200 --> 00:03:41.700
It's fine.

00:03:41.700 --> 00:03:43.700
I'll move forward.

00:03:43.700 --> 00:03:45.410
One of the reasons
why I like photography

00:03:45.410 --> 00:03:48.940
is the ability to create
things that are epic.

00:03:48.940 --> 00:03:52.010
I like to bring stories to life.

00:03:52.010 --> 00:03:54.950
I think growing up as a kid,
I've always wanted-- you know,

00:03:54.950 --> 00:03:56.450
I've always read
books-- fantasies--

00:03:56.450 --> 00:03:58.650
and every kid wants to be
a knight in shining armor,

00:03:58.650 --> 00:03:59.850
riding a horse whatever.

00:03:59.850 --> 00:04:01.750
And suddenly I'm
in the situation

00:04:01.750 --> 00:04:03.990
where I'm able to take these
visions that I had a kid

00:04:03.990 --> 00:04:04.948
and bring them to life.

00:04:04.948 --> 00:04:06.820
I'm able to find people,
connect with them,

00:04:06.820 --> 00:04:09.389
and make something that really
shouldn't exist in reality

00:04:09.389 --> 00:04:11.430
and just kind of bring it
into the present, which

00:04:11.430 --> 00:04:13.130
is really, really amazing.

00:04:13.130 --> 00:04:16.110
A shoot like this comes
together completely randomly.

00:04:16.110 --> 00:04:21.200
I was actually sitting-- I
was actually just on Facebook

00:04:21.200 --> 00:04:24.130
going through my messages, and
some dude from a medieval store

00:04:24.130 --> 00:04:25.490
hits me up and says,
hey, I've seen your work.

00:04:25.490 --> 00:04:26.610
I'd love to work on
something together.

00:04:26.610 --> 00:04:28.610
You should come by our
store and check it out.

00:04:28.610 --> 00:04:29.630
I said, sure, why not.

00:04:29.630 --> 00:04:32.010
Went in, played dress
up for a couple hours.

00:04:32.010 --> 00:04:34.060
And before we knew
it, we just started

00:04:34.060 --> 00:04:36.800
talking about the possibility
of doing something together.

00:04:36.800 --> 00:04:38.750
He had these amazing costumes.

00:04:38.750 --> 00:04:41.445
And they said, you know,
we have about a two week

00:04:41.445 --> 00:04:42.820
window where we
can do something.

00:04:42.820 --> 00:04:45.734
We have all the stock in
from the new collection.

00:04:45.734 --> 00:04:47.400
Would you like to do
something together?

00:04:47.400 --> 00:04:49.983
And I said, well, I'm going to
head off to Europe really soon.

00:04:49.983 --> 00:04:52.055
It didn't look that
feasible, but you know,

00:04:52.055 --> 00:04:53.930
it was too cool of a
project to pass through.

00:04:53.930 --> 00:04:54.870
So we had two weeks.

00:04:54.870 --> 00:04:56.811
And before I left
the store that day,

00:04:56.811 --> 00:04:58.310
we had already
locked on a location.

00:04:58.310 --> 00:04:59.990
It was this medieval village.

00:04:59.990 --> 00:05:02.630
And all I had to do was find
people to wear suits of armor.

00:05:02.630 --> 00:05:04.421
So I went on Facebook,
hit it up, and said,

00:05:04.421 --> 00:05:07.460
who wants to dress up as
medieval soldiers on a weekend?

00:05:07.460 --> 00:05:08.960
And I ended up with
about 50 people.

00:05:08.960 --> 00:05:10.750
And we ended up in this
really surreal situation

00:05:10.750 --> 00:05:12.350
where we had these
guys just watching

00:05:12.350 --> 00:05:15.360
these beautiful sketches
that I had made.

00:05:15.360 --> 00:05:17.190
And this huge number
of people actually

00:05:17.190 --> 00:05:20.230
ended up showing
up-- over 50 people

00:05:20.230 --> 00:05:22.990
within the space of two weeks,
just to come and dress up

00:05:22.990 --> 00:05:25.170
and have a great time.

00:05:25.170 --> 00:05:27.032
You know, this was in Montreal.

00:05:27.032 --> 00:05:29.240
It was right at spring, so
we had this crazy weather.

00:05:29.240 --> 00:05:33.480
We had everything from
hail to rain to sun.

00:05:33.480 --> 00:05:34.570
It made no sense.

00:05:34.570 --> 00:05:36.710
But even though this
was a product that

00:05:36.710 --> 00:05:38.550
was purely creative,
there was no money,

00:05:38.550 --> 00:05:41.120
there was nothing involved,
all these people still got out.

00:05:41.120 --> 00:05:44.990
And I think it's because
you almost bring back

00:05:44.990 --> 00:05:48.312
a certain sense of nostalgia
to people where they can relive

00:05:48.312 --> 00:05:50.270
something that they would
never have the chance

00:05:50.270 --> 00:05:51.920
to live otherwise.

00:05:51.920 --> 00:05:55.830
And this is really--
50 people in the middle

00:05:55.830 --> 00:05:58.340
of this barn with fire,
with all these props,

00:05:58.340 --> 00:06:01.360
and it's absolutely crazy.

00:06:01.360 --> 00:06:03.010
Another reason why
I love photography

00:06:03.010 --> 00:06:06.660
is the ability to create
things that are different.

00:06:06.660 --> 00:06:09.240
This was a shot that
I did for a metal band

00:06:09.240 --> 00:06:11.580
by the name of The Agonist,
and they reached out to me.

00:06:11.580 --> 00:06:13.920
Once again, they only
had a two week deadline.

00:06:13.920 --> 00:06:19.724
And they needed to come out
with shots where they just

00:06:19.724 --> 00:06:21.390
wanted anything that
would be different,

00:06:21.390 --> 00:06:23.210
anything that would
stand out, anything

00:06:23.210 --> 00:06:25.250
that would make them a little
bit different from the crowd.

00:06:25.250 --> 00:06:27.374
Because the minute you type
"metal band" in Google,

00:06:27.374 --> 00:06:28.140
what do you find?

00:06:28.140 --> 00:06:31.960
Well, you find this-- a group
of people with their arms

00:06:31.960 --> 00:06:35.180
crossed against a solid black
background looking badass.

00:06:35.180 --> 00:06:36.432
And you know, that's not fun.

00:06:36.432 --> 00:06:37.640
Everyone does the same thing.

00:06:37.640 --> 00:06:39.800
So when they said we
want something different,

00:06:39.800 --> 00:06:40.640
we just started brainstorming.

00:06:40.640 --> 00:06:41.550
What could we come up with?

00:06:41.550 --> 00:06:43.300
And they said, a fight
scene would be fun.

00:06:43.300 --> 00:06:44.170
So we said, why not?

00:06:44.170 --> 00:06:45.640
And then we had to
find a location,

00:06:45.640 --> 00:06:47.430
so I said loading dock, perhaps?

00:06:47.430 --> 00:06:49.010
Loading dock on my studio.

00:06:49.010 --> 00:06:50.110
And then we needed props.

00:06:50.110 --> 00:06:52.850
So props-- in my case,
we had a minimal budget.

00:06:52.850 --> 00:06:56.000
So we went to a dumpster, and we
just collected a bunch of crap

00:06:56.000 --> 00:07:00.630
and just decorated this loading
dock, and did our photo shoot.

00:07:00.630 --> 00:07:02.074
Took about one entire day.

00:07:02.074 --> 00:07:03.490
At the end of the
day, we came out

00:07:03.490 --> 00:07:05.580
with an image that
really was conceivably

00:07:05.580 --> 00:07:07.770
one of the most iconic
images that they've ever had.

00:07:07.770 --> 00:07:09.170
And the cool thing about
people that want you

00:07:09.170 --> 00:07:11.400
because you're different,
because you stand out,

00:07:11.400 --> 00:07:13.060
is that they're going to
want to hire you again

00:07:13.060 --> 00:07:14.101
for the next time around.

00:07:14.101 --> 00:07:16.946
So this time they
had a new singer,

00:07:16.946 --> 00:07:19.320
and they wanted to introduce
a new singer into the group.

00:07:19.320 --> 00:07:20.361
So we did the same thing.

00:07:20.361 --> 00:07:22.890
We got them all
together, and they

00:07:22.890 --> 00:07:25.710
wanted to figure out a way
to introduce the new singer

00:07:25.710 --> 00:07:27.010
in a post-apocalyptic setting.

00:07:27.010 --> 00:07:30.910
So we said, hey, why
not suspend the girl

00:07:30.910 --> 00:07:34.390
and put in this factory kind
of setting and do a shoot?

00:07:34.390 --> 00:07:38.100
So I started Googling for
a forge-- which we found--

00:07:38.100 --> 00:07:41.050
and looking for ways to
suspend the girl, which we also

00:07:41.050 --> 00:07:41.637
figured out.

00:07:41.637 --> 00:07:44.220
And initially I want to do this
whole Photoshop deconstruction

00:07:44.220 --> 00:07:47.410
where pieces of her legs
were coming off and really

00:07:47.410 --> 00:07:49.972
cybernetic, but they
didn't want people

00:07:49.972 --> 00:07:51.930
to think that their new
singer was handicapped.

00:07:51.930 --> 00:07:54.220
So at the end of the day, she
needed all of her body parts,

00:07:54.220 --> 00:07:55.720
and we suspended her,
and did all this stuff.

00:07:55.720 --> 00:07:57.320
And there's actually going
to be a before and after.

00:07:57.320 --> 00:07:58.361
I'll show you guys later.

00:08:01.260 --> 00:08:03.600
Other reasons why
I love photography

00:08:03.600 --> 00:08:05.710
is the adventures
that it brings,

00:08:05.710 --> 00:08:08.550
the places that it brings you
that are completely unexpected.

00:08:08.550 --> 00:08:11.454
This was a shot that I took
in Belgium for a retoucher

00:08:11.454 --> 00:08:12.870
by the name of
Chester van Bommel.

00:08:12.870 --> 00:08:15.580
And I met Chester
on the internet,

00:08:15.580 --> 00:08:18.425
because I was looking at a
photographer whose work I quite

00:08:18.425 --> 00:08:20.300
enjoy-- her name is
Viona Art-- and I noticed

00:08:20.300 --> 00:08:22.508
on the bottom there was a
tiny little line that said,

00:08:22.508 --> 00:08:23.920
retouched by Chester van Bommel.

00:08:23.920 --> 00:08:25.110
And I'm like, hey,
this guy's pretty cool.

00:08:25.110 --> 00:08:26.400
He's got some great stuff.

00:08:26.400 --> 00:08:28.710
So I hit him up and said,
hey, we should work together.

00:08:28.710 --> 00:08:31.118
And that conversation
just-- it blossomed.

00:08:31.118 --> 00:08:32.909
We did a couple creative
products together.

00:08:32.909 --> 00:08:34.820
And then the time came when I
was actually going to Europe,

00:08:34.820 --> 00:08:37.400
and I said, you know, it
would be a really fun project

00:08:37.400 --> 00:08:39.220
to kind of take a shot of you.

00:08:39.220 --> 00:08:42.030
Show off what goes on in
the mind of a retoucher.

00:08:42.030 --> 00:08:44.069
And so we started
brainstorming different ideas,

00:08:44.069 --> 00:08:44.860
different concepts.

00:08:44.860 --> 00:08:46.420
I ended up in Belgium.

00:08:46.420 --> 00:08:49.360
I wanted to find a place that
was so grandiose that people

00:08:49.360 --> 00:08:52.955
would automatically assume
it's Photoshopped but wasn't.

00:08:52.955 --> 00:08:55.340
So I found an urban
explorer, who brought us

00:08:55.340 --> 00:08:57.810
to this place,
which is, I think,

00:08:57.810 --> 00:08:59.797
an abandoned stock exchange.

00:08:59.797 --> 00:09:01.880
And I did everything my
parents told me not to do,

00:09:01.880 --> 00:09:03.796
so that's meet up with
a stranger at 5 o'clock

00:09:03.796 --> 00:09:06.610
in the morning in a random
parking lot for the first time,

00:09:06.610 --> 00:09:09.410
and then go into a
manhole off on the street

00:09:09.410 --> 00:09:11.280
in the middle of
another foreign country.

00:09:11.280 --> 00:09:13.490
But then you end up in
this crazy situation,

00:09:13.490 --> 00:09:15.615
this crazy location,
that you would never ever

00:09:15.615 --> 00:09:17.740
have the chance to be in
unless I had a good excuse

00:09:17.740 --> 00:09:18.170
to go out there.

00:09:18.170 --> 00:09:19.730
Because I would never wake
up at 5 in the morning,

00:09:19.730 --> 00:09:21.524
I'd never talk to a
stranger, I would never

00:09:21.524 --> 00:09:23.190
go into a manhole to
end up in the place

00:09:23.190 --> 00:09:24.439
if I wasn't doing photography.

00:09:24.439 --> 00:09:26.704
So photography for me is
really about the experiences

00:09:26.704 --> 00:09:28.370
that I get to enjoy
through photography.

00:09:31.611 --> 00:09:33.360
Other things that I
love about photography

00:09:33.360 --> 00:09:35.193
are the technical
challenges that it brings.

00:09:35.193 --> 00:09:38.100
This was a shoot that I
did in a swimming pool.

00:09:38.100 --> 00:09:42.370
And I wanted to come up with
a different idea with one

00:09:42.370 --> 00:09:44.090
of my body painters.

00:09:44.090 --> 00:09:46.640
And we came up with the
idea of suspending a camera

00:09:46.640 --> 00:09:49.050
with a crane over a swimming
pool with some black lights

00:09:49.050 --> 00:09:51.800
going over, because it
hadn't been done before.

00:09:51.800 --> 00:09:54.120
So we ended up with this
crazy set, this whole group

00:09:54.120 --> 00:09:56.980
of people, with our super
high tech secure setting,

00:09:56.980 --> 00:10:01.000
here as you can see roped
together, MacGyvered together.

00:10:01.000 --> 00:10:02.760
And the shoot came together.

00:10:02.760 --> 00:10:05.580
I mean, it was probably one of
the most technically difficult

00:10:05.580 --> 00:10:06.790
shoots that I had ever done.

00:10:06.790 --> 00:10:09.150
Everything went
wrong in that shoot.

00:10:09.150 --> 00:10:12.390
And you know, I came up with
all these crazy ideas initially

00:10:12.390 --> 00:10:14.340
when sitting down with
this makeup artist.

00:10:14.340 --> 00:10:15.840
We were kind of
trying to figure out

00:10:15.840 --> 00:10:18.250
what hadn't been done before,
what would be really cool.

00:10:18.250 --> 00:10:20.166
Then we thought black
lights, but black lights

00:10:20.166 --> 00:10:23.150
had been done-- you know,
rave parties and all that.

00:10:23.150 --> 00:10:23.820
Not super cool.

00:10:23.820 --> 00:10:25.540
Then we wanted to sink the
black lights underwater

00:10:25.540 --> 00:10:26.670
and do a shoot
there, and then we

00:10:26.670 --> 00:10:28.150
didn't have the
technology to do it.

00:10:28.150 --> 00:10:29.420
So finally we
settled for something

00:10:29.420 --> 00:10:32.220
in the middle, which was suspend
the black lights over the water

00:10:32.220 --> 00:10:34.970
and have these characters body
painted kind of popping out

00:10:34.970 --> 00:10:36.050
through the surface.

00:10:36.050 --> 00:10:37.940
And I had this whole
storyline planned out.

00:10:37.940 --> 00:10:39.315
These are my
beautiful sketches--

00:10:39.315 --> 00:10:43.590
which is why I'm a photographer
not an artist-- of dropping

00:10:43.590 --> 00:10:45.299
a girl in the middle
of like a bed sheet.

00:10:45.299 --> 00:10:46.756
We thought it'd
look like a flower.

00:10:46.756 --> 00:10:47.810
It could symbolize birth.

00:10:47.810 --> 00:10:50.170
And that didn't work out--
the girl almost drowned.

00:10:50.170 --> 00:10:51.420
Well, she didn't almost drown.

00:10:51.420 --> 00:10:53.674
We had safety around, but
it just didn't look good.

00:10:53.674 --> 00:10:55.090
Then the next shoot
I wanted to do

00:10:55.090 --> 00:10:56.570
was tie these two
people together

00:10:56.570 --> 00:10:58.790
on the bottom of
the water to create

00:10:58.790 --> 00:11:00.784
like a tree kind
of a looking thing.

00:11:00.784 --> 00:11:02.950
That was supposed to symbolize
some kind of a union.

00:11:02.950 --> 00:11:04.908
And that didn't work,
because they could hardly

00:11:04.908 --> 00:11:07.670
swim on their own, let
alone being tied together.

00:11:07.670 --> 00:11:09.370
So that wasn't going to happen.

00:11:09.370 --> 00:11:11.094
So that went completely south.

00:11:11.094 --> 00:11:12.510
Then I had this
other idea where I

00:11:12.510 --> 00:11:15.437
wanted to create these little
like tadpole-looking things,

00:11:15.437 --> 00:11:17.020
these three creatures,
which were just

00:11:17.020 --> 00:11:19.874
supposed to symbolize
some form of life.

00:11:19.874 --> 00:11:21.040
And this one kind of worked.

00:11:21.040 --> 00:11:23.830
We took a rope, we dragged
all these three characters

00:11:23.830 --> 00:11:26.250
across the swimming pool and
just get them enough momentum

00:11:26.250 --> 00:11:28.037
so they're just floating along.

00:11:28.037 --> 00:11:29.870
And it worked, but it
didn't look very good.

00:11:29.870 --> 00:11:32.136
Then I had the first
breath of life,

00:11:32.136 --> 00:11:34.510
which was these three characters
coming out of the water,

00:11:34.510 --> 00:11:35.390
which is the one you just saw.

00:11:35.390 --> 00:11:36.890
Then I had death,
which was supposed

00:11:36.890 --> 00:11:39.306
to be the three of them lying
one on top of another, which

00:11:39.306 --> 00:11:41.460
looked remarkably like
life, but just not as good.

00:11:41.460 --> 00:11:43.835
So at the end of the day, I
had these elaborate concepts.

00:11:43.835 --> 00:11:47.450
We spent about 12, 10 hours
shooting the entire thing.

00:11:47.450 --> 00:11:49.120
A whole bunch of
things went wrong,

00:11:49.120 --> 00:11:50.620
but I got one good
shot out of it.

00:11:50.620 --> 00:11:54.550
And I suppose the moral of the
story is, I tried something.

00:11:54.550 --> 00:11:57.170
I push hard to try and achieve
it, failed a bunch of things

00:11:57.170 --> 00:11:59.420
along the way, but now I
know where my limitations lie

00:11:59.420 --> 00:12:01.120
on what I can achieve,
and what I can't achieve,

00:12:01.120 --> 00:12:03.220
and which parts to push,
and which parts to grow.

00:12:03.220 --> 00:12:05.270
And I really enjoy those
technical challenges,

00:12:05.270 --> 00:12:07.436
because if it were easy,
it wouldn't be worth doing.

00:12:09.459 --> 00:12:11.000
Other things I love
about photography

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:12.458
are the inspirational
people that I

00:12:12.458 --> 00:12:13.570
get to meet along the way.

00:12:13.570 --> 00:12:16.060
I think photography
opens up windows,

00:12:16.060 --> 00:12:18.030
and it's an avenue
of communication

00:12:18.030 --> 00:12:20.309
that everybody has access to.

00:12:20.309 --> 00:12:21.850
Doesn't matter if
you're rich, you're

00:12:21.850 --> 00:12:23.350
poor-- everyone
can look at a photo

00:12:23.350 --> 00:12:24.730
and understand
and appreciate it.

00:12:24.730 --> 00:12:27.519
And this has opened up
countless doors for me,

00:12:27.519 --> 00:12:29.310
just because I can just
reach out to people

00:12:29.310 --> 00:12:30.601
and say, hey, I do photography.

00:12:30.601 --> 00:12:32.486
I really like what you do.

00:12:32.486 --> 00:12:33.860
Let's work on
something together.

00:12:33.860 --> 00:12:35.901
And that's kind of my way
to connect with people.

00:12:35.901 --> 00:12:38.480
So this is a shot of
the Underwater Realm.

00:12:38.480 --> 00:12:39.980
And the Underwater
Realm is a group

00:12:39.980 --> 00:12:41.360
of independent filmmakers.

00:12:41.360 --> 00:12:43.651
Dave Reynolds-- the guy
sitting on the director's chair

00:12:43.651 --> 00:12:46.360
underwater-- actually decided
to make a series of short films

00:12:46.360 --> 00:12:48.943
underwater, and that's something
that hadn't been done before.

00:12:48.943 --> 00:12:50.800
So they Kickstarted
I think $150,000.

00:12:50.800 --> 00:12:53.730
And that guy's
like 26 years old,

00:12:53.730 --> 00:12:56.780
retaining a whole crew
of like 50 to 100 people

00:12:56.780 --> 00:12:59.960
for a two-year period--
all volunteers-- just

00:12:59.960 --> 00:13:01.460
to make this series
of short films

00:13:01.460 --> 00:13:02.420
that hadn't been done before.

00:13:02.420 --> 00:13:04.836
So when I saw their Kickstarter
campaign, I was like, wow,

00:13:04.836 --> 00:13:05.640
you are so cool.

00:13:05.640 --> 00:13:07.120
I want get to know you.

00:13:07.120 --> 00:13:08.620
I want to be a part
of your project.

00:13:08.620 --> 00:13:09.869
I want to participate in this.

00:13:09.869 --> 00:13:11.090
So I sent an email out.

00:13:11.090 --> 00:13:13.420
Surprisingly, they
replied, and they said,

00:13:13.420 --> 00:13:16.217
we'd love to work with
you, but you're in Montreal

00:13:16.217 --> 00:13:17.050
and we're in London.

00:13:17.050 --> 00:13:18.480
And at the time, I still
had an engineering job,

00:13:18.480 --> 00:13:20.400
so it just didn't
seem very feasible.

00:13:20.400 --> 00:13:22.970
But the connection had been
made, and that was great.

00:13:22.970 --> 00:13:24.200
Fast forward eight
months down the line.

00:13:24.200 --> 00:13:26.800
I was looking for inspirational
people across Europe to shoot.

00:13:26.800 --> 00:13:28.190
And I reached out to them
again, and I said, hey,

00:13:28.190 --> 00:13:29.420
would you like to be
a part of my project?

00:13:29.420 --> 00:13:31.378
And this time around, it
just ended up working.

00:13:31.378 --> 00:13:33.990
So I ended up in the middle
of the swimming pool,

00:13:33.990 --> 00:13:38.780
working with these guys who,
for me, are super inspirational.

00:13:38.780 --> 00:13:41.635
And I think those interactions
are so priceless and so

00:13:41.635 --> 00:13:43.706
impossible to have otherwise.

00:13:43.706 --> 00:13:46.570
You know, who goes through
these great lengths?

00:13:46.570 --> 00:13:50.470
They had this videographer
who shoots for the BBC.

00:13:50.470 --> 00:13:52.700
At the time, not many
underwater RED EPIC housings,

00:13:52.700 --> 00:13:54.520
and he came,
volunteered his time,

00:13:54.520 --> 00:13:56.800
just flew himself in just
to be a part of the project.

00:13:56.800 --> 00:13:58.170
They built entire
sets underwater.

00:13:58.170 --> 00:14:00.086
And I wasn't part of
this, because my shot was

00:14:00.086 --> 00:14:03.370
under the trial phase, but
to see this come together

00:14:03.370 --> 00:14:05.920
and to know that I actually
played a part in all of this

00:14:05.920 --> 00:14:08.010
is absolutely phenomenal.

00:14:08.010 --> 00:14:11.840
And it wouldn't have been
possible without photography.

00:14:11.840 --> 00:14:14.820
And last but not least, the
reason why I love photography

00:14:14.820 --> 00:14:17.220
is the ability to inspire
people, the ability

00:14:17.220 --> 00:14:20.660
to connect with
people of all levels.

00:14:20.660 --> 00:14:24.680
This was a shoot that I did,
and it was done in Florida.

00:14:24.680 --> 00:14:27.027
We made all the piece
of the costumes.

00:14:27.027 --> 00:14:28.610
We made the angel
wings, and all that.

00:14:28.610 --> 00:14:32.700
And how it came
together was I put up

00:14:32.700 --> 00:14:37.620
a photo of me breathing fire,
and this girl who is a Facebook

00:14:37.620 --> 00:14:40.540
friend tagged one of her friends
in it, and she left a comment

00:14:40.540 --> 00:14:43.070
and said, oh my
gosh, I'm never going

00:14:43.070 --> 00:14:44.622
to be as good as this guy.

00:14:44.622 --> 00:14:46.080
And I left the
comment, and I said,

00:14:46.080 --> 00:14:48.484
oh, try putting your camera
to this and this setting.

00:14:48.484 --> 00:14:50.400
And then she was like,
oh my gosh, he replied!

00:14:50.400 --> 00:14:52.590
And she sent me like this
huge Facebook message,

00:14:52.590 --> 00:14:54.490
just telling me that she'd
love for me to check out

00:14:54.490 --> 00:14:56.323
her portfolio, that she
was a video student,

00:14:56.323 --> 00:14:57.830
that she was also
a make-up artist.

00:14:57.830 --> 00:14:59.980
And then it took me about
a week to reply to her,

00:14:59.980 --> 00:15:01.650
but eventually when
we did reconnect,

00:15:01.650 --> 00:15:03.510
I learned that she was also
a special effects artist,

00:15:03.510 --> 00:15:06.310
she was off in Florida, and this
conversation just started out.

00:15:06.310 --> 00:15:11.894
And she said-- it started off
as this dare-- and she said,

00:15:11.894 --> 00:15:13.310
is there anything
that you've ever

00:15:13.310 --> 00:15:15.980
wanted to shoot that you haven't
had the chance to shoot yet?

00:15:15.980 --> 00:15:17.640
And then for some
reason, I said,

00:15:17.640 --> 00:15:19.311
I've always wanted
to shoot angel wings.

00:15:19.311 --> 00:15:21.310
I want someone to build
some angel wings for me.

00:15:21.310 --> 00:15:22.480
And she said, if
you come to Florida,

00:15:22.480 --> 00:15:23.970
I'll make the angel
wings for you.

00:15:23.970 --> 00:15:26.166
And I said, if you make
the angel wings for me,

00:15:26.166 --> 00:15:27.290
I'll fly myself to Florida.

00:15:27.290 --> 00:15:28.860
And she said, OK, and
she started making them.

00:15:28.860 --> 00:15:29.440
And I'm like aw, crap!

00:15:29.440 --> 00:15:30.710
So I've got to buy a ticket now.

00:15:30.710 --> 00:15:32.250
So I bought myself
a ticket to Florida.

00:15:32.250 --> 00:15:33.590
And we didn't really know
what we're going to do.

00:15:33.590 --> 00:15:35.700
And it all started off
with just this idea

00:15:35.700 --> 00:15:37.366
that we're going to
shoot a fallen angel

00:15:37.366 --> 00:15:38.620
in the middle of the forest.

00:15:38.620 --> 00:15:40.370
And I got to the first day.

00:15:40.370 --> 00:15:43.320
We went scouting, and we
saw this magical forest,

00:15:43.320 --> 00:15:45.160
and I just came up
with these ideas on how

00:15:45.160 --> 00:15:47.680
it would be nice to get the
concept even more elaborate.

00:15:47.680 --> 00:15:49.369
And by the time of
the shoot itself,

00:15:49.369 --> 00:15:50.410
it just scaled itself up.

00:15:50.410 --> 00:15:53.240
We ended up, I think, with
seven models, full costumes

00:15:53.240 --> 00:15:55.260
that we had built over
the space of a week.

00:15:55.260 --> 00:15:59.860
These wings were actually built
with just some packing plastics

00:15:59.860 --> 00:16:01.800
that we just strapped
to coat hangers,

00:16:01.800 --> 00:16:04.350
and we dusted off with charcoal.

00:16:04.350 --> 00:16:06.389
And it's just absolutely
cool and crazy to be

00:16:06.389 --> 00:16:07.680
able to do something like this.

00:16:07.680 --> 00:16:11.110
And on top of that, a company
called SmugMug-- actually based

00:16:11.110 --> 00:16:14.780
out of Mountainview--
also noticed this project.

00:16:14.780 --> 00:16:18.840
And they told me that since
I was in the United States,

00:16:18.840 --> 00:16:20.850
they'd love to come down
and document my work,

00:16:20.850 --> 00:16:22.850
because they thought it
was really inspirational

00:16:22.850 --> 00:16:25.744
and they wanted to share this
vision with just the community.

00:16:25.744 --> 00:16:27.410
So they flew their
own videographer down

00:16:27.410 --> 00:16:28.940
to make this piece
over here that I

00:16:28.940 --> 00:16:30.480
thought was
absolutely fantastic.

00:16:33.470 --> 00:16:36.980
Being creative has just
become a way of life.

00:16:36.980 --> 00:16:38.790
I don't think it
begins with the desire

00:16:38.790 --> 00:16:41.370
to wake up in the morning
and say, today, I'm creative.

00:16:41.370 --> 00:16:43.559
It just comes down to
today, I want to live,

00:16:43.559 --> 00:16:45.725
I want to do what I love,
and so I'm going to go out

00:16:45.725 --> 00:16:47.110
and I'm going to do that.

00:16:47.110 --> 00:16:49.275
My name is Benjamin von
Wong, and I'm an artist.

00:16:54.264 --> 00:16:56.430
I like to think of my
photography as something epic,

00:16:56.430 --> 00:16:58.440
something larger than life.

00:16:58.440 --> 00:17:00.230
It takes a vision
and exaggerates it,

00:17:00.230 --> 00:17:02.604
so that you can't tell the
difference between what's real

00:17:02.604 --> 00:17:05.099
and what's fake.

00:17:05.099 --> 00:17:07.456
I take a concept, and I
transform it into reality.

00:17:10.135 --> 00:17:11.760
I mean, I don't just
take the pictures.

00:17:11.760 --> 00:17:16.000
I conceptualize, I design them,
I create them, I build them up.

00:17:16.000 --> 00:17:17.460
It starts off with
a base concept,

00:17:17.460 --> 00:17:19.020
it starts off with an
idea, and it slowly

00:17:19.020 --> 00:17:20.730
builds up, based on
the constraints that

00:17:20.730 --> 00:17:21.450
have available.

00:17:21.450 --> 00:17:24.010
It's all about finding
solutions to make something that

00:17:24.010 --> 00:17:25.750
is seemingly impossible
and making it

00:17:25.750 --> 00:17:28.459
to something that is
better than reality.

00:17:31.730 --> 00:17:32.230
I

00:17:32.230 --> 00:17:33.570
Think that people
see photography

00:17:33.570 --> 00:17:35.420
as clicking a button,
getting the lighting right,

00:17:35.420 --> 00:17:36.660
getting the composition
right, but it's

00:17:36.660 --> 00:17:37.618
so much more than that.

00:17:37.618 --> 00:17:40.150
Being able to connect with
people is so important,

00:17:40.150 --> 00:17:41.640
and it shows in
the final results.

00:17:41.640 --> 00:17:42.800
If you understand
the story that you're

00:17:42.800 --> 00:17:43.940
trying to tell,
then suddenly they

00:17:43.940 --> 00:17:46.460
can translate that emotion,
making the image that much more

00:17:46.460 --> 00:17:47.840
powerful.

00:17:47.840 --> 00:17:49.820
I think that photos
can transport people

00:17:49.820 --> 00:17:51.760
into another universe,
into another world,

00:17:51.760 --> 00:17:53.647
and it becomes,
you know, a story.

00:17:53.647 --> 00:17:54.980
And people try to figure it out.

00:17:54.980 --> 00:17:56.670
They want to understand
what's going on,

00:17:56.670 --> 00:17:57.961
and that just makes it magical.

00:18:00.345 --> 00:18:02.470
I think that if you start
doing the things that you

00:18:02.470 --> 00:18:04.480
love, and you start sharing
the things that you love, then

00:18:04.480 --> 00:18:06.273
sooner or later, people
start hiring you to do things

00:18:06.273 --> 00:18:08.410
that you love, for your
passion, for your vision,

00:18:08.410 --> 00:18:10.800
for what makes you
unique, and because you're

00:18:10.800 --> 00:18:13.560
the only person that can
do whatever that thing is

00:18:13.560 --> 00:18:16.060
because you love it so much.

00:18:16.060 --> 00:18:19.685
My name is Benjamin von
Wong, and I a creative.

00:18:19.685 --> 00:18:23.670
So just think it's super cool
that a company would actually

00:18:23.670 --> 00:18:26.960
be so interested in what
I do that they would

00:18:26.960 --> 00:18:29.540
be willing to fly their own
person down to film this

00:18:29.540 --> 00:18:31.080
and share it with the world.

00:18:31.080 --> 00:18:34.540
And you meet people by
doing what you love,

00:18:34.540 --> 00:18:35.950
by being passionate
about things.

00:18:35.950 --> 00:18:37.380
And having the ability
to connect with people,

00:18:37.380 --> 00:18:39.670
you meet the people that
believe in what you do too.

00:18:39.670 --> 00:18:41.820
Incidentally, the reason
why I'm here today

00:18:41.820 --> 00:18:44.630
is because SmugMug decided
to bring me in and just say,

00:18:44.630 --> 00:18:48.630
hey, we really love what you
do, and we'd love to support it.

00:18:48.630 --> 00:18:49.130
Come down.

00:18:49.130 --> 00:18:50.190
We'll commission
some shoots for you.

00:18:50.190 --> 00:18:52.270
We don't really know what
we want to shoot yet.

00:18:52.270 --> 00:18:55.060
And we ended up suspending
some of their employees

00:18:55.060 --> 00:18:58.890
off of a 40 story
building just yesterday,

00:18:58.890 --> 00:19:01.180
with a camera dangling
nine feet off the ledge

00:19:01.180 --> 00:19:03.330
on this massive C-stand.

00:19:03.330 --> 00:19:05.362
We did a shoot so
that their employees

00:19:05.362 --> 00:19:07.070
could come and attend,
off in the forest,

00:19:07.070 --> 00:19:08.940
which is the one we
actually went to see,

00:19:08.940 --> 00:19:13.700
where we had designers flying
in from LA, five models coming

00:19:13.700 --> 00:19:16.850
in, just freezing their day
off in Sutro forest just to be

00:19:16.850 --> 00:19:18.420
a part of all these projects.

00:19:18.420 --> 00:19:20.739
And it's really, really
something amazing.

00:19:20.739 --> 00:19:22.280
And it didn't really
always start off

00:19:22.280 --> 00:19:23.320
with-- you don't
really start off

00:19:23.320 --> 00:19:25.194
saying like, oh, I want
to be an inspiration.

00:19:25.194 --> 00:19:26.970
I want to inspire people.

00:19:26.970 --> 00:19:30.950
It actually began with me-- when
I started giving presentations

00:19:30.950 --> 00:19:32.500
like these, I didn't
really know what

00:19:32.500 --> 00:19:33.708
I was supposed to talk about.

00:19:33.708 --> 00:19:37.220
So I went on Facebook and
I started asking for help.

00:19:37.220 --> 00:19:39.850
And I want to ask people what
they thought about my work,

00:19:39.850 --> 00:19:43.392
and have I made a difference,
have I contributed to them,

00:19:43.392 --> 00:19:45.350
have I touched them in
any way, shape, or form?

00:19:45.350 --> 00:19:48.314
And I got the predictable-- you
know, all the answers about how

00:19:48.314 --> 00:19:50.230
technically they've
learned a bunch of things.

00:19:50.230 --> 00:19:53.280
But then I came
across this one post

00:19:53.280 --> 00:19:54.584
by the name of Tyler Grace.

00:19:54.584 --> 00:19:56.250
And he said, I'm a
19-year-old teenager,

00:19:56.250 --> 00:19:57.670
and I've lived half
my life in a hospital

00:19:57.670 --> 00:19:59.360
thanks to a few
chronic illnesses.

00:19:59.360 --> 00:20:01.030
I had no passion or drive
to do anything in life

00:20:01.030 --> 00:20:01.900
at the beginning of last year.

00:20:01.900 --> 00:20:03.515
But in about May or
June, I came across you,

00:20:03.515 --> 00:20:05.060
